# Purpose

This document defines the coding standards for Nimbus Platform.

The objective is consistency, readability, maintainability, and long-term evolution—not personal preference.

These standards apply equally to:

- Human developers
- AI coding agents
- Code reviewers
- Open source contributors

If code violates these standards, it should not be merged.

---

# Guiding Principles

Nimbus values:

- Readability over brevity
- Explicitness over magic
- Simplicity over cleverness
- Consistency over preference
- Maintainability over optimization

Every line of code should be understandable by a new engineer.

---

# General Rules

## Write Self-Documenting Code

Prefer descriptive names.

Good:

```ts
calculateAverageTemperature()
```

Avoid:

```ts
calcAvg()
```

---

## Small Functions

Functions should perform one responsibility.

Preferred maximum:

- 30–40 lines

If a function becomes difficult to describe in one sentence, split it.

---

## Single Responsibility

Classes, services, and modules should have one primary reason to change.

Avoid "God classes."

---

## Avoid Deep Nesting

Prefer:

```ts
if (!device) return;

processDevice(device);
```

Instead of:

```ts
if (device) {
    if (device.station) {
        if (...)
```

Maximum nesting depth:

3 levels

---

## Prefer Composition

Favor composition over inheritance.

Avoid inheritance unless modeling a true "is-a" relationship.

---

# Naming Conventions

## Variables

camelCase

```ts
deviceId
temperatureReading
lastHeartbeat
```

---

## Functions

camelCase

Use verbs.

```ts
createStation()
assignDevice()
calculateDewPoint()
```

---

## Classes

PascalCase

```ts
TelemetryService
DeviceRepository
AlertEvaluator
```

---

## Interfaces

PascalCase

Do NOT prefix with "I".

Good:

```ts
TelemetryPayload
```

Bad:

```ts
ITelemetryPayload
```

---

## Enums

PascalCase

Members in PascalCase.

```ts
enum AlertSeverity {
    Critical,
    High,
    Medium,
    Low
}
```

---

## Constants

UPPER_SNAKE_CASE

```ts
MAX_RETRY_ATTEMPTS
DEFAULT_TIMEOUT_MS
```

---

## Files

Use kebab-case.

```
device-service.ts

alert-controller.ts

telemetry-repository.ts
```

---

# TypeScript Standards

Strict mode is mandatory.

Never disable strict typing.

Never use:

```ts
any
```

Instead:

```ts
unknown
```

or

proper generics.

---

Always define return types on exported functions.

Good:

```ts
function createDevice(): Device
```

---

Prefer readonly whenever possible.

```ts
readonly stationId
```

---

Use enums sparingly.

Prefer literal unions when appropriate.

---

# Error Handling

Never ignore exceptions.

Never swallow errors.

Bad:

```ts
catch {}
```

Always log meaningful context.

```ts
logger.error({
    deviceId,
    stationId,
    error
});
```

Return domain-specific errors.

Avoid generic Error objects.

---

# Logging

Use structured logging.

Never use:

```ts
console.log()
```

Production logging uses Pino.

Every log should include relevant identifiers.

Example:

```ts
logger.info({
    organizationId,
    deviceId,
    stationId
});
```

---

# API Standards

Controllers should remain thin.

Controller responsibilities:

- Receive request
- Validate request
- Call service
- Return response

Controllers must never:

- Query Prisma
- Contain business rules
- Perform calculations

---

# Repository Standards

Repositories own persistence only.

Repositories may:

- Query database
- Save entities
- Delete entities

Repositories may NOT:

- Validate requests
- Apply business rules
- Send notifications

---

# Service Standards

Services own business logic.

Services may:

- Coordinate repositories
- Publish events
- Execute business rules

Services should not know HTTP implementation details.

---

# Validation Standards

Validate all external input.

Validation must occur before business logic.

Use:

- Zod

Never manually validate request bodies.

---

# Async Code

Always use async/await.

Avoid nested Promise chains.

Good:

```ts
await repository.save(device);
```

Avoid:

```ts
repository.save(device)
.then(...)
.catch(...)
```

---

# Comments

Code should explain itself.

Comments explain WHY.

Not WHAT.

Bad:

```ts
// Increment counter
counter++;
```

Good:

```ts
// Prevent duplicate telemetry processing
```

---

# Imports

Import order:

1. Node modules

2. External packages

3. Internal packages

4. Relative imports

Alphabetize within groups.

---

# Testing Standards

Business logic must be unit testable.

Repository tests:

Integration

Controllers:

Integration

Utility functions:

Unit

Critical workflows:

End-to-End

---

# Performance Guidelines

Do not optimize prematurely.

Optimize when:

- Measured
- Repeatable
- Justified

Prefer clarity over micro-optimizations.

---

# Security Standards

Never trust external input.

Never expose stack traces.

Never hardcode:

- Secrets
- API Keys
- Passwords

Always use environment variables.

---

# Documentation Standards

Every exported class and function should be understandable from its name.

Complex modules require README documentation.

Architecture changes require an ADR.

---

# AI Agent Rules

AI agents must:

- Follow naming conventions
- Preserve existing style
- Avoid unnecessary abstractions
- Keep files focused
- Reuse shared packages
- Never duplicate code
- Prefer consistency over creativity

If uncertain, match the surrounding codebase.

---

# Pull Request Checklist

Every PR should satisfy:

✓ Builds successfully

✓ Passes lint

✓ Passes tests

✓ Uses shared contracts

✓ Uses shared validation

✓ Updates documentation

✓ No architectural violations

✓ No duplicated logic

✓ No unused code

✓ No console.log

✓ No commented-out code

---

# Definition of Clean Code

Nimbus code is considered clean when it is:

Readable

Predictable

Testable

Secure

Consistent

Documented

Strongly Typed

Observable

Easy to Refactor

Easy to Extend

---

# Success Criteria

A new contributor should be able to:

- Read the code
- Understand the intent
- Navigate the architecture
- Add a feature
- Write tests

without needing tribal knowledge.

Consistency is more valuable than individual coding style.